The screen between the Altars and the Nave proper is several times referred to as the Valence‚2 and is probably intended by the “ bars '' in the will of William Asshe in 1406.

In the Nave we are able to fix exactly the position of the Pulpit, which, from the wills of Thomas Roos and William Robynson in 1 52 9, appears to have been against the first pillar of the Nave proper on the north side3 on the south side of that pillar Mr. Shepherd’s plan of the tombs shows a void space, where it is probable that the Pulpit stood. It is no doubt this pillar that Alice Lucas in 1524 described as standing within “ burdes and pykes '’; she may have meant either the Pulpit itself or a railing round it ; supposing that the Pulpit was only a boarded platform with a rail round about the psslar, the description would be reasonable enough.

The position of the Organ is given in the will of Nicholas Pembyrton in 1519, who was to be buried on the north side of the Choir in our Lady Chapel by the Organs. We know that Pembyrton's tomb was towards the west end of the Chapel of S. Mary.
